libsnmp: Reassign timeout value for select(2)

As select may update the timeout value, the code may not sleep for
100 ms. If timeout is updated, the code will only sleep for 1 ms once
and the immediately return from select(2).
Reassign the timeout value in the loop shouldn't be harmful even on
systems that don't update the timeout value.

Add Linux 6.7 compatibility parsing /proc/net/snmp

Linux 6.7 adds a new OutTransmits field to Ip in /proc/net/snmp.
This breaks the hard-coded assumptions about the Ip line length.
Add compatibility to parse Linux 6.7 Ip header while keep support
for previous versions.

EtherLike-MIB: Optimize interface_dot3stats_get_errorcounters()

This patch may fix an infinite loop. See also
https://github.com/net-snmp/net-snmp/issues/780.

EtherLike-MIB: Simplify dot3stats_interface_name_list_free()

Change the return type from 'int' into 'void'.
CHANGES: Add -Wredundant-decls to the developer options

CHANGES: Remove more redundant redeclarations

Prepare for enabling -Wredundant-decls.

mib2c: Fix re-initialization of tables

Allows re-initialization of tables, if e.g. a table needs to be
registered under a different snmp-context or to a different agent on a
different IP. The table can be re-initialized with different
configuration.

Problem solved here is that the table info is reset to no configuration
before re-initializing. E.g. the snmp indexes are added during
initialization, but not removed in shutdown. To make sure we clear all
configuration from the table, a memset() was chosen: we start with a
clean table.

CHANGES: Remove redundant declarations

These changes aim to remove redundant declarations from the Net-SNMP
source code. They are most easily exposed with adding -Wredundant-decls
to CPPFLAGS for the gcc compiler.
Redundant declarations in other used modules and mib2c generated code are
left in place.

The changes consist of:
- Removal of duplicate declarations in header files, other or the same.
- Removal of duplicate declarations in source files, where the prototype
already exists in the appropriate header file.
- Fixing declaration of register log handler functions.
- Use of forward declared struct, rather than extern function or char.
